From: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
Date: Mon, 06 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qualcomm: ppe: give a virtual port a routable ingress

The downlink offload - a wired-to-wireless flow forwarded to a virtual
port - leaves the port's ingress L3 interface unbound, because only
that direction crosses the hardware. Bind it: a virtual port now takes
the same port-to-L3-interface binding as a physical port, so a packet
that enters the PPE with the virtual port as its source is routed and
NAT'd by the flow engine like any ingress. It reuses the L3 interface
the downlink already programs with the router MAC, which is the one the
reverse (wireless-to-wired) flow of the connection resolves.

This is dormant on its own - nothing injects a packet sourced from a
virtual port yet - and only completes the port's programming. The
transmit and receive-interception paths that offload the wireless
uplink follow.

Signed-off-by: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_flowtable.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_flowtable.c
@@ -1033,12 +1033,13 @@ static int ppe_ft_flow_replace(struct pp
 			goto err_my_mac;
 
 		/* The port binding classifies plain ingress on the
-		 * port; PPPoE ingress resolves its L3 interface
-		 * through the session table instead, and a virtual
-		 * port has no hardware ingress at all (only the
-		 * wired-to-wireless direction is offloaded).
+		 * port, and a virtual port takes it too so that a
+		 * wireless-uplink packet injected with the port as
+		 * its source is routed by the same flow entry; PPPoE
+		 * ingress resolves its L3 interface through the
+		 * session table instead.
 		 */
-		if (data.pppoe_sid < 0 && flow->vp < 0) {
+		if (data.pppoe_sid < 0) {
 			ret = ppe_port_l3_if_set(ft->ppe_dev, nh.port,
 						 nh.l3_if);
 			if (ret)
